50|$|As {{the silver}} Indian rupee {{was a popular}} coin locally (reduced in value from 30 to 27 stuivers in 1735), a local version of it was issued in 1747, with Arabic text (reading 'Dirham money of the Dutch Company' and 'For the island Java the Great'), and only the date in Roman script, valued at 30 stuivers, {{identical}} in weight to the Surat rupee of the Mughal Empire. This continued only until in 1750, as it did not generate much profit. Subsequently, as with <b>imported</b> <b>gold</b> coinage, some <b>imported</b> rupees were counterstamped between 1753 and 1761, and given a 30 stuiver value.|$|R
