50|$|India imports {{in excess}} of 1000 tons {{annually}} (including unofficially smuggled gold) with negligible local production. The annual <b>gold</b> <b>imports</b> are around 50 billion US$ next only to crude oil imports widening the trade deficit. In the years since 2001 to 2015, the official net <b>gold</b> <b>imports</b> are 269 billion US$ whereas the Foreign Institutional Investors (FII) invested only 157 billion US$ in Indian equities. <b>Gold</b> <b>imports</b> cost is nearly 3% of the GDP. Alarmed by the huge trade deficit in the year 2012, GoI introduced moderate customs duty (below 10%) on <b>gold</b> <b>imports.</b> Though the policy is fetching good customs income, the imports demand is not drastically coming down. It {{is due to the}} reason that world gold demand is mainly driven by Indians and its price is fixed by Indians in Indian rupees. Imposing customs tax on <b>gold</b> <b>imports</b> in India or devaluation of Indian currency, led to the softening of its international price but remained range bound in rupee terms. Customs duty imposition also led to increase in gold smuggling but narrowed the trade deficit to permissible limit as the smuggled gold would not get accounted as imports in trade deficit calculations.|$|R
